    <title>Combined summary - Criminal complaints against "network disruption as a service" startups</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T18:38:45.224976+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-March/007694.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>There have been discussions about the legality of collecting publicly available information from the Bitcoin P2P network, particularly in relation to Chainalysis, a blockchain analytics firm. While some argue that analyzing publicly available information is necessary for transaction verification and research, there are concerns about potential violations of privacy laws and third-party disclosure of collected information. This issue of surveillance could lead to legal action against corporations conducting it. Developers are being urged to work on providing anonymity options for users to protect against such surveillance.In another discussion, the behavior of certain clients and the definition of a node in a network were debated. Simplified Payment Verification (SPV) clients were included as pretending to be a network peer without relaying transactions. A proposal was made for funding network resources using crowdfunding contracts involving group signatures being extended in both directions to prove server and client participation in the funded group. This system is relatively anonymous, allowing any client to use any node they funded or buy priority access.Mike Hearn criticized Chainalysis for allegedly breaking the Bitcoin protocol by deploying nodes that pretend to be network peers but do not behave as one, causing issues for other peers. The conversation also included a proposal for network users to pay for the node resources they consume to compensate node operators for the burden. Legal issues around surveillance on the Bitcoin network were also raised, with some arguing that it may lead to legal action against those conducting it. Finally, there were discussions about reviewing laws related to computer fraud and abuse acts and making the responsibilities of network peers more explicit in the protocol.There are concerns about the legality of Chainalysis nodes and other blockchain-related services, with questions about whether following protocol specs and keeping logs would still be considered a violation. The message shared warns against surveillance on the network and gathering information for later use, suggesting that these operations cease to avoid legal repercussions. Chainalysis has defended its operations, stating that monitoring the public blockchain is essential for research and transaction verification purposes. However, there are potential legal issues related to violation of Swiss laws and concerns over whether log analysis could incriminate those who give IP addresses away.Developers must work towards giving users an anonymity option which can be exercised as part of any transaction. Additionally, a new protocol concept called abis.io has been introduced for enabling decentralization and expansion of a giving economy and social good. For those interested in bitcoin development, websites like lists.sourceforge.net provide valuable information. Keybase.io/odinn gives access to the PGP signature for verifying authenticity.It is noted that privacy laws do not apply in cases where users voluntarily provide information publicly. Different countries have different interpretations of user privacy, leading to legal implications surrounding surveillance and gathering information. It remains to be seen how this will all play out. On a separate note, the Go Parallel website serves as a hub for all things parallel software development, developed in partnership with Slashdot Media and sponsored by Intel. Additionally, a Bitcoin-development mailing list is available at https://lists.sourceforge.net/lists/listinfo/bitcoin-development, encouraging community participation and collaboration in the Bitcoin space.</summary>
